  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Lusignan","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Normand, Andre, Francois, Lucien, Marcel.","French: habitational name from Lusignan, a place in Vienne. This surname is very rare in France. Compare   Zeno  .","History: Jean Miel (or Amiel) <i>dit</i> Lusignan from Lusignan in Vienne, France, married Marie-Thérèse Latouche in Boucherville, QC, in 1699. — A French family called <i>(de) Lusignan</i> became enormously powerful in the eastern Mediterranean during the Middle Ages. Guy de Lusignan (1129–94) was king of Cyprus from 1192 to 1194 (and before that, by right of marriage, king of the crusader state of Jerusalem). Hugues de Lusignan was king of Cyprus from 1267 to 1284 and king of Jerusalem from 1268 to 1284. During the 14th century, Lusignans became kings of the Armenian kingdom of Cilicia (on the Mediterranean coast of what is now Turkey, facing Cyprus)."],"variants":[{"name":"Zeno","meanings":["Italian (mainly southern Italy), Hispanic (mainly Puerto Rico), and African American: from the personal name <i>Zeno</i>, classical Greek <i>Zēnōn</i>, a derivative of <i>Zeus</i>, the name of the king of the gods in Greek mythology. <i>Zeno</i> or <i>Zenone</i> is the name of a 4th-century Italian saint from Verona. As an African American name it was probably adopted in honor of the Stoic philosopher Zeno of Kition.","Altered form of French   Lusignan  ."]}]},{"name":"Marie","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of   Maria .  When first introduced to England in the Middle Ages, it was Anglicized in pronunciation and respelled   Mary .  This French form was reintroduced into the English-speaking world as a separate name in the 19th century, and is still pronounced more or less in the French manner, although sometimes with the stress on the first syllable. It is now often used in combination with other names such as <i>Ellie</i>, <i>Chloe</i>, and <i>Lisa</i>."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Marie de Lusignan was born before March 1215, in Cyprus. She married Gautier IV de Brienne Comte de Brienne, de Jaffa et d’Ascalon in 1233. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. She died on 5 July 1251, in her hometown."},"et":{"Bef March 1215–5 juillet 1251":"enne märtsi 1215–5. juuli 1251","1205–1246":"1205–1246","1235–1296":"1235–1296","1240–1261":"1240–1261","1240–1296":"1240–1296","1215–1251":"1215–1251","1205":"1205","1215":"1215","1235":"1235","1246":"1246","5 juillet 1251":"5. juuli 1251","1233":"1233","1296":"1296","1240":"1240","1251":"1251","1261":"1261","Bef March 1215":"enne märtsi 1215","Le Caire, Égypte":"Káhira, Egiptus","Cyprus":"Küpros","Chypre":"Küpros","Europa":"Europe","Brienne-le-Château, Aube, Champagne-Ardenne, France":"Brienne-le-Château, Aube, Champagne-Ardenne, Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"Bef March 1215–5 juillet 1251":"ennen vuotta maaliskuu 1215–5. heinäkuuta 1251","1205–1246":"1205–1246","1235–1296":"1235–1296","1240–1261":"1240–1261","1240–1296":"1240–1296","1215–1251":"1215–1251","1205":"1205","1215":"1215","1235":"1235","1246":"1246","5 juillet 1251":"5. heinäkuuta 1251","1233":"1233","1296":"1296","1240":"1240","1251":"1251","1261":"1261","Bef March 1215":"ennen vuotta maaliskuu 1215","Le Caire, Égypte":"Káhira, Egypti","Cyprus":"Kypros","Chypre":"Kypros","Europa":"Europe","Brien